Fukushima and the collapse of derivatives
CAMBRIDGE – Financial commentators have equated the Japanese earthquake, tsunami, and nuclear disaster with the role of derivatives in the 2008 financial crisis.
The similarity is quite clear: each of these activities generates large profits and involves a very low but explosive risk.
Yet, the similarity between the two types of crisis ends where the way to prevent their recurrence begins.
In the case of the Fukushima nuclear power plant, a once-in-a-century flood, combined with design flaws that are usually harmless, caused the shutdown of cooling water circulation in the reactors and significant radiation leaks.
With regard to financial markets, an unanticipated collapse in real estate values, combined with design flaws in derivative and repo markets, has damaged the ability of major financial institutions to meet their debts.
Although the underlying risks originate outside the systems — a tsunami for Fukushima, excessive investment in mortgage loans for financial institutions — design flaws and bad luck have caused the systems to be unable to contain the damage.
In the United States, AIG, Bear Stearns, and Lehman Brothers — all with significant investments in derivatives and/or repos — went bankrupt, causing a freeze in credit on the markets for several long weeks.
We now understand fairly well the risks and design flaws of Fukushima.
One cannot say the same about the risks of derivatives, which caused the global economy to waver.
At Fukushima, teams of workers bravely attempt to stop the radiation leaks.
On the contrary, for derivatives, similar efforts are misdirected and will not allow us to avoid the next financial crisis.
We are recreating similar derivative products and financial structures, over the same errors that are still active.
Financial actors use financial instruments to transfer risk: for example, one actor accepts the risk of euro fluctuations but does not want the risk on the yen, whereas for another, it will be the opposite.
In this case, the first promises to provide euros on June 1st, and the second promises to provide yen.
If one currency loses value compared to the other, the loser pays the difference.
Repos are financial transactions.
Financial firms sell assets, such as Treasury bonds or mortgage-backed debt, for cash and promise to repurchase these assets later, typically the following day (hence the name "repo," which is an abbreviation for the English verb repurchase – or repurchase, note by the translator).
The problem is that the cash coming from these short-term repos represents a large part of the balance sheets of the most important financial institutions, which implies that even minor financial tremors can heavily affect them.
Some institutions may then find themselves deprived of repo financing, as in 2008, and go bankrupt, like Bear Stearns.
Taken individually, derivative transactions or repos are not to blame.
Each one separately legitimately transfers the risk to those better able to bear it, or allows for financial participation.
However, when they are overused by institutions that are systemically vital, they can cause the financial system to collapse, due to its design flaws.
Even today, about 70% of the liabilities of major American financial firms is made up of very short-term loans, such as repos payable the next day.
In the United States, the main design flaws are found in bankruptcy legislation, which exempts derivatives and repos from most usual constraints in the event of bankruptcy.
For example, investors who hold derivative contracts or repos with financially weakened institutions can seize the company's assets before — and at the expense of — its normal creditors. In doing so, they can decide its fate, whereas with a little more time, the company in question might have been able to survive.
Such actions ruined AIG, Bear Stearns, and others during the financial crisis.
Worse still, because investors in derivatives and repos find themselves at the front of the line for repayments in so many ways, they have less incentive to encourage market discipline by closely scrutinizing the solvency of their counterparties and carefully rationing their exposure to any single counterparty.
Typically, they will be repaid, anyway.
Surely, someone must be first.
Other financial actors must bear more risk because the exemptions for derivatives and repo participants place them at the forefront in the event of bankruptcy.
Normally, one would expect others to therefore have an interest in encouraging more market discipline.
But the actor that follows in line is often the American government, as the guarantor of "too-big-to-fail" financial institutions (too important to allow them to go bankrupt, ed.). However, the government is ill-suited to regulate these markets on a day-to-day basis.
It is not financially agile; it often confines itself to the regulated market; and, when economic conditions are good, no official would want to spoil the party.
The American Congress had an opportunity to address this flaw in the major overhaul of finance that it adopted last summer through the Dodd-Frank bill.
But it did not seize it.
If investors in derivatives, repos, and credit-default swaps (credit event derivatives, ed.) did not receive preferential treatment, they would behave differently.
First and foremost, they would more often insist that their counterparties be adequately capitalized.
They accepted the risk generated by extremely low capitalization when it essentially involved American government money; they would be less inclined to do so if it was their own money at stake.
The public perceives Fukushima-type risks and derivative-related risks differently.
Many people fear nuclear risks, which are striking and have caused a slowdown in the sector that must deal with security concerns.
But derivative and repo markets present risks that are poorly understood, difficult to communicate in the media, and complicated to debate and resolve for politicians.
During a crisis, these markets attract public attention and contempt, but when the economy stabilizes again, ordinary people lose all interest, leaving the financial sector to control its own fate with the legislative body.
Regarding Fukushima-type risks, analysts are already discussing how nuclear power plants can be designed and built to contain earthquake and tsunami-related risks through passive cooling systems.
It is now considered possible to design nuclear power plants capable of keeping fuel rods cool even in the event of a complete loss of electrical power.
On the contrary, little significant progress has been made so far in preventing the damage that the priority given to derivatives and repos in the event of bankruptcy could cause during a new financial system crisis.
New rules are being developed, which require end users (such as oil companies using derivatives to hedge against unanticipated changes in oil prices) and others to post high-quality collateral.
However, these rules do not address the main problem: the weak incentives for market discipline for the major financial institutions.
It is as if we are reacting to Fukushima by better controlling gas emissions in oil extraction projects.
We should examine how to fully make investors in derivatives and repos assume the risk associated with their decisions when they conduct transactions with financially vital systemic institutions.
Instead, we survived the 2008 financial tsunami only to rebuild in the same place, with the same financial flaws and according to the same faulty design.
